  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
        <div rend="parallel">
          <p xml:id="KT127-kilavi">pāṇaṉ vāyilākap pukkavaḻit talaimakaṟkut tōḻi colliyatu.</p>
          <p xml:lang="en">Uttered to the confidante for HIM, when the bard entered as a mediator.</p>
          </div>


        <div rend="parallel">
            <lg xml:id="KT127">
<l>                kurukukoḷak kuḷitta keṇṭai yayala</l>
<l>                turukeḻu tāmarai vāṉmukai verūuṅ</l>
<l>                kaḻaṉiyam paṭappaik kāñci yūra</l>
<l>                voruniṉ pāṇaṉ poyya ṉāka</l>
<l>                vuḷḷa pāṇa rellāṅ</l>
<l>                kaḷvar pōlvarnī yakaṉṟici ṉōrkkē.</l>
             </lg>
            <lg xml:lang="en">
           <l>O man from the village of Kāñci trees in the gardens near the fields,</l>
           <l rend="indent">
            <choice>
                <seg>where the barb, diving because it takes [it] for a heron,</seg>
                <seg>where the barb(?), dived, because the heron [will] take [it],</seg>
            </choice>
           </l>
           <l rend="indent">is startled by the sky[-bright] bud of the lotus of [similar] form,<note place="foot">Is <term xml:lang="ta">urukeḻu</term> here epitheton ornans (beautiful lotus) or does it belong into the image (lotus of heron-like form)? Is the wording deliberately open to make both associations possible?</note></l>
           <l>– if your one bard is a liar,<note place="foot">It is tempting to read the infinitive <term xml:lang="ta">āka</term> here as a conditional and to understand ā like Skt. bhū in a merely predicative way. Srin.'s alternative is, however: "since your one bard turns out to be a liar".</note></l>
           <l>all bards are<note place="foot">Here the syntax is not unequivocal. It would also be possible to read <term xml:lang="ta">pāṇar ellām</term> as the subject to <term xml:lang="ta">kaḷvar pōlvar</term>. This sentence division presupposes a completion of the missing predicate noun in the pāṇar line, which is preferable from the point of view of contents, because it results in a climax from liar to robber.</note> in fact.<note place="foot">Is <term xml:lang="ta">uḷḷa</term>, infinitive of <term xml:lang="ta">uḷ</term>, to be taken here adverbially ("as it is")? TVG takes it as the peyareccam: "all bards that exist".</note></l>
           <l>They are like robbers to those you have left.</l>
            </lg>
        </div>
    </body>
